# Git Workflow

After fully completing a task, always perform a git commit and push.

## When to Commit

Commit only when:
- The task is fully done (all files changed, code compiles, no broken state)
- The change is atomic — one commit = one logical unit of work

## Commit Message Format

Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/):

```
<type>: <short description>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`, `test`, `docs`

Examples:
- `feat: add refresh token rotation`
- `fix: resolve duplicate session on login`
- `refactor: extract auth guards to separate module`

## Steps to Follow

1. `git add .`
2. `git commit -m "<type>: <description>"`
3. `git push`

## Rules

- Never commit broken or intermediate code
- Never use `git push --force` on `main`/`master`
- One concern per commit — don't mix unrelated changes
